We can already describe the Node.JS version required for an NPM package:
https://www.npmjs.org/doc/files/package.json.html#engines

```
{ "engines" : { "node" : ">=0.10.3 <0.12" } }
{ "engines" : { "npm" : "~1.0.20" } }
```

Do you think it would be helpful to annotate precisely which language standards that our code expects in order to run? For example:

```
{ "engines" : { "ecmascript" : ">=5" } }
{ "engines" : { "coffeescript" : ">=1.7.0 <1.8" } }
```

With this convention, our tooling could automatically transpile certain modules. `browserify` itself could (one day) even perform some of these steps automatically, making configuration simpler in certain cases.

This PR allows us changing the file tree before compiling. Here is the way I use it;

``` js
b.plugin(function (b) {
     var pack = b.pack;

     b.pack = function (opts) {
       opts.sourceTransform = through(function (row) {
         // change the row
         this.queue(row);
       });

       return pack.call(this, opts);
     };
});
```
